# Phase 2 — Scraper Engine Implementation

Implement all 9 provider scrapers and the full normalize → validate → English-filter → deduplicate → store pipeline, integrated with BullMQ for scheduled and on-demand job processing. This replaces the Phase 1 placeholder scraper and stubs.

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Architecture Decision — HTTP API vs. Redis Queue for Scraper ↔ Backend Communication**: The ARU mentions BullMQ as the job queue, but the Python scraper and NestJS backend are separate containers. I recommend the scraper **polls a Redis-backed BullMQ queue** for job messages AND **pushes scraped results directly to PostgreSQL** (not through the NestJS API) for performance. The NestJS backend enqueues jobs to Redis, the Python worker dequeues and processes them. Status/results are written to the DB and Redis, which the backend reads directly. **Please confirm or propose an alternative.**

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Scraper Scope — Site Accessibility**: Some of the 9 coupon sites may have changed URLs, blocked scraping, or gone offline since the ARU was written. I will implement all 9 scrapers against current site structures, but some may need to be marked `is_enabled: false` by default if the site is inaccessible. The scraper architecture is built so adding/fixing individual providers is a low-risk change. **Please confirm this is acceptable.**

> [!WARNING]
> **No Udemy API Integration**: The scrapers extract data from coupon aggregator sites only — they do NOT call the Udemy API. Course verification (is the coupon still valid?) relies on checking the coupon URL reachability, not Udemy's API. This is consistent with the ARU.

